line_1: WHEN home I return'd from the dancing last night,
line_2: And elate by your praises attempted to write,

line_1: And elate by your praises attempted to write,
line_2: WHEN home I return'd from the dancing last night,

line_1: I familiarly call'd on Apollo for aid,
line_2: And told him how many fine things you had said;

line_1: And told him how many fine things you had said;
line_2: I familiarly call'd on Apollo for aid,

line_1: He smil'd at my folly, and gave me to know,
line_2: Your wit, and not mine, by your writing you shew;

line_1: Your wit, and not mine, by your writing you shew;
line_2: He smil'd at my folly, and gave me to know,

line_1: And then, says the God, still to make you more vain,
line_2: He hath promis'd that I shall enlighten your brain,

line_1: He hath promis'd that I shall enlighten your brain,
line_2: And then, says the God, still to make you more vain,

line_1: When he knows in his heart, if he speak but his mind,
line_2: That no woman alive can now boast I am kind:

line_1: That no woman alive can now boast I am kind:
line_2: When he knows in his heart, if he speak but his mind,

line_1: For since Daphne to shun me grew into a laurel,
line_2: With the sex I have sworn still to keep up the quarrel.

line_1: I thought it all joke, 'till by writing to you,
line_2: I have prov'd his resentment, alas! but too true.
